<body>
    <h1>ISG Developer Training</h1>
    <div class=3D"Section1">
        <p></p>
<div class=3D"">
<div class=3D"childtabs-macro" data-fixed-position=3D"false">
<div class=3D"aui-tabs horizontal-tabs" data-aui-responsive=3D"true">
<strong style=3D"text-decoration: underline" class=3D"pageTitle" data-conte=
nt-id=3D"1173255044">Section 1: Scan pipeline</strong>
<div class=3D"tabs-pane active-pane" id=3D"b7a649a3-9c35-4976-bc9c-1e6593b1=
ec19-1173255044">
<h3 id=3D"Section1:Scanpipeline-Howitworks"><span class=3D"TextRun SCXW9402=
2319 BCX0" style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);"><span class=3D"NormalTextRun SCXW94=
022319 BCX0">How it works&nbsp;</span></span><span class=3D"EOP SCXW9402231=
9 BCX0" style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);">&nbsp;</span></h3>
<p><strong>Below is an overview of the different test environments &amp; th=
e deployment pipeline&nbsp;</strong></p>
<p><span>When developing on the WDP platform, there are several testing env=
ironments which follow in a progressive order.&nbsp;</span><span>A deployme=
nt must be successful in one testing environment before proceeding to the n=
ext or higher testing environments.</span></p>
<p><span> In some environments, (namely SVP and PRD), an important success =
criterion for a complete deployment is for the the development team to reci=
eve a <strong>digital signature</strong> from an ISG code scan. </span></p>
<p><span>The process is as follows:</span></p>
<ol>
<li><span>A Fortify scan is initially triggered automatically when a deploy=
ment is made to the SIT environment.&nbsp;</span>
<ul>
<li><span>Artefacts&nbsp;Produced: FPR uploaded to Fortify,&nbsp;automated =
results to developer who made the&nbsp;</span>deployment (as seen below)</l=
i>
</ul></li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin-left: 60.0px;"><span class=3D"confluence-embedded-file-w=
rapper confluence-embedded-manual-size"><img class=3D"confluence-embedded-i=
mage" draggable=3D"false" height=3D"193" src=3D"88b5b9b0c0fb397605f9cd63941=
2cc38078accb0a7fd70b2d3d2dc14a02d8c26" data-image-src=3D"/download/attachme=
nts/1173255044/image2022-11-2_10-39-48.png?version=3D1&amp;modificationDate=
=3D1667345988587&amp;api=3Dv2" data-unresolved-comment-count=3D"0" data-lin=
ked-resource-id=3D"1232602040" data-linked-resource-version=3D"1" data-link=
ed-resource-type=3D"attachment" data-linked-resource-default-alias=3D"image=
2022-11-2_10-39-48.png" data-base-url=3D"https://confluence.srv.westpac.com=
.au" data-linked-resource-content-type=3D"image/png" data-linked-resource-c=
ontainer-id=3D"1173255044" data-linked-resource-container-version=3D"10" al=
t=3D"" width=3D"468"></span></p>
<ol>
<li>The scan will trigger an automated email (as seen above) to the individ=
ual who triggered the deployment. This report will contain the code scan re=
port detailing the findings.=20
<ul>
<li>If no new medium or high rated issues are found, the automated results =
will contain both a summary of the issues found, and a digital signature (s=
ee digital stamp link in above screenshot) which will allow that build to p=
roceed to other environments. ISG Build Signature can be seen by clicking o=
n the link in the automated email - Digital Stamp.</li>
<li>If however new high or medium issues (see <em>unaudited issues: 7)</em>=
 in below screenshot) are found in the Fortify scan, the digital signature =
will not be provided and the deployment will be marked as incomplete (as se=
en below example where no digital stamp is provided).</li>
</ul></li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin-left: 60.0px;"><span class=3D"confluence-embedded-file-w=
rapper confluence-embedded-manual-size"><img class=3D"confluence-embedded-i=
mage" draggable=3D"false" width=3D"468" src=3D"d57b7bb09b50cfd1f04d278f2103=
14b338bd920de88183495a48afdd8f496e3f" data-image-src=3D"/download/attachmen=
ts/1173255044/image2022-11-2_10-53-11.png?version=3D1&amp;modificationDate=
=3D1667346791277&amp;api=3Dv2" data-unresolved-comment-count=3D"0" data-lin=
ked-resource-id=3D"1232602164" data-linked-resource-version=3D"1" data-link=
ed-resource-type=3D"attachment" data-linked-resource-default-alias=3D"image=
2022-11-2_10-53-11.png" data-base-url=3D"https://confluence.srv.westpac.com=
.au" data-linked-resource-content-type=3D"image/png" data-linked-resource-c=
ontainer-id=3D"1173255044" data-linked-resource-container-version=3D"10" al=
t=3D"" height=3D"276"></span></p>
<p><span>When deploying to SVP and PROD, the scan is <strong>not</strong> t=
riggered again but the build is checked for a digital signature. If a digit=
al signature is not generated for a particular build deployed to SIT, that =
build will not get deployed successfully in SVP or PROD.</span><span>&nbsp;=
</span></p>
<p><span class=3D"confluence-embedded-file-wrapper confluence-embedded-manu=
al-size"><img class=3D"confluence-embedded-image" draggable=3D"false" width=
=3D"468" src=3D"fa60b66d8d82d32dca4b87f8cdbfc1bd6b34e9b562cf1f442517364a570=
51754" data-image-src=3D"/download/attachments/1173255044/image2022-11-2_10=
-32-44.png?version=3D1&amp;modificationDate=3D1667345564340&amp;api=3Dv2" d=
ata-unresolved-comment-count=3D"0" data-linked-resource-id=3D"1232602003" d=
ata-linked-resource-version=3D"1" data-linked-resource-type=3D"attachment" =
data-linked-resource-default-alias=3D"image2022-11-2_10-32-44.png" data-bas=
e-url=3D"https://confluence.srv.westpac.com.au" data-linked-resource-conten=
t-type=3D"image/png" data-linked-resource-container-id=3D"1173255044" data-=
linked-resource-container-version=3D"10" alt=3D"" height=3D"143"></span></p=
>
<p><span>&nbsp;</span></p>
<p><br></p>
</div><strong style=3D"text-decoration: underline" class=3D"pageTitle" data=
-content-id=3D"1173255056">Section 2: Common security issues found in APIs =
&amp; recommendations</strong>
<div class=3D"tabs-pane active-pane" id=3D"b7a649a3-9c35-4976-bc9c-1e6593b1=
ec19-1173255056">
<h1 id=3D"Section2:CommonsecurityissuesfoundinAPIs&amp;recommendations-1Vul=
nerableNPMpackages"><strong><span class=3D"TextRun SCXW208439831 BCX0" styl=
e=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);"><span class=3D"NormalTextRun SCXW208439831 BCX0">1=
 Vulnerable NPM packages&nbsp;</span></span><span class=3D"EOP SCXW20843983=
1 BCX0" style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);">&nbsp;</span></strong></h1>
<p><strong>Cause:&nbsp;</strong>An insecure version of a specific package i=
s being used by the development team and it is flagged by Fortify.&nbsp;</p=
>
<p><strong>Fix:&nbsp;</strong>When there are vulnerable NPM packages found =
in APIs, there are two scenarios which each have their own way forward:&nbs=
p;</p>
<ol>
<li>The vulnerable package has a patch available.&nbsp;=20
<ul>
<li>In this case, the dev team will need to update the package.&nbsp;&nbsp;=
</li>
<li>If updating breaks the build and the team is required to deploy to prod=
, they will have to risk accept and get SOM / SBD approval. Once they have =
SOM and SBD approval, inform AppSec consultant via engagement or email <a h=
ref=3D"mailto:SecureCodeReview@westpac.com.au" class=3D"external-link" rel=
=3D"nofollow">SecureCodeReview@westpac.com.au</a> with the API name and the=
 details. SOM approval is for when a component is not part of an SBD engage=
ment.&nbsp;</li>
</ul></li>
<li>The vulnerable package does not have a patch available.&nbsp;=20
<ul>
<li>The dev team is to ensure that this is the case, they may confirm with =
WDP and/or conduct their own research. The dev team must also make a detail=
ed comment against the issue in Fortify. Inform AppSec consultant via engag=
ement or email <a href=3D"mailto:SecureCodeReview@westpac.com.au" class=3D"=
external-link" rel=3D"nofollow">SecureCodeReview@westpac.com.au</a> with th=
e API name and the details and wait for a response.&nbsp;&nbsp;</li>
</ul></li>
</ol>
<p>Note: if a library does not have a patch for an extended period (more th=
an 6-12 months), it would not be best practice to continue using it.&nbsp;<=
/p>
<p>Where there is no project engagement and the API is unable to use a non-=
vulnerable version of a package, a Security Policy Exemption must be lodged=
.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>
<p><span>&nbsp;</span></p>
<h1 id=3D"Section2:CommonsecurityissuesfoundinAPIs&amp;recommendations-2Sec=
retsmanagement(plaintextpasswordsandsecrets)"><strong>2 Secrets management =
(plaintext passwords and secrets)&nbsp;</strong></h1>
<p><strong>Cause</strong>: There have been multiple instances of secrets (s=
pecifically, passwords) stored in configuration files. Storing a plaintext =
password in a configuration file may result in a system compromise. If plai=
ntext passwords or secrets are stored in configuration files, Fortify will =
flag these issues and it will block builds being deployed into higher envir=
onments.&nbsp;</p>
<p><strong>Fix</strong>: WDP has thorough documentation for secrets managem=
ent standards for WDP APIs. Please go through the following confluence page=
 in detail and ensure there are no plaintext passwords or credentials in co=
nfiguration files. Please also ensure that if you are working on API develo=
pment that you have completed both the general induction and developer indu=
ction.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>
<p>To learn more about API Environment Secrets Management, please visit <a =
href=3D"https://confluence.srv.westpac.com.au/display/WDPIPAAS/API+Environm=
ent+Secrets+Management" rel=3D"nofollow">this </a>WDP Confluence page.</p>
<p><br></p>
<h1 id=3D"Section2:CommonsecurityissuesfoundinAPIs&amp;recommendations-3Cro=
ss-OriginResourceSharing(CORS)Misconfiguration"><strong>3 Cross-Origin Reso=
urce Sharing (CORS) Misconfiguration&nbsp;</strong></h1>
<p><strong>Cause</strong>: Cross Origin Resource Sharing (CORS) is a mechan=
ism which allows controlled access to resources located outside of a given =
domain. It extends and adds flexibility for the Same Origin Policy (SOP). I=
t also provides potential for cross-domain attacks if a website=E2=80=99s C=
ORS policy is poorly configured and implemented. If the =E2=80=98Access-con=
trol-allow-origin' header is set to be a wildcard, the application=E2=80=99=
s data would be accessible to JavaScript running on any domain (trusted and=
 untrusted).&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>
<p>response.addHeader("Access-Control-Allow-Origin", "*");&nbsp;</p>
<p><strong>Fix</strong>: Do not use a wildcard to define the access-control=
-allow origin header. Instead, provide an explicit list of trusted domains.=
&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>
<p>response.addHeader("Access-Control-Allow-Origin", <a href=3D"http://www.=
trusted.com/" class=3D"external-link" rel=3D"nofollow">www.trusted.com</a>)=
;&nbsp;</p>
<p>Avoid setting the header value to null: Access-Control-Allow-Origin: nul=
l. Cross origin resource calls from internal documents or sandboxed request=
s can specify null.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>
<p><span>&nbsp;</span></p>
<h1 id=3D"Section2:CommonsecurityissuesfoundinAPIs&amp;recommendations-4Inj=
ectionVulnerabilities"><strong>4 Injection Vulnerabilities&nbsp;</strong></=
h1>
<p>Injection vulnerabilities occur when an attacker is able to send malicio=
us data to an interpreter.</p>
<p>Almost any source of data can be an injection vector which leads to mult=
iple types of injection vulnerabilities. The common types include:&nbsp;</p=
>
<p style=3D"margin-left: 30.0px;"><strong>4.1 Path manipulation&nbsp;</stro=
ng></p>
<p style=3D"margin-left: 30.0px;"><strong>Cause</strong>: Path manipulation=
 vulnerabilities occur when user-controlled data or input is placed in a fi=
le or URL path that is used on the server to access local resources. If vul=
nerable, an attacker can modify the file path to access resources which mig=
ht contain sensitive information. Even if the attack is constrained within =
the web root, it may be possible to retrieve application config files, sour=
ce code for server-side scripts, etc. Moreover, attackers may also gain the=
 ability to modify or delete important data such as over-writing an importa=
nt configuration file.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>
<p style=3D"margin-left: 30.0px;"><strong>Fix</strong>: Ideally, user-contr=
ollable data should not need to be placed in file or URL paths. Known files=
 should be referenced via an index number rather than their names. If this =
is considered unavoidable, then user-controlled data should be strictly val=
idated against a whitelist of accepted values.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>
<p><br></p>
<p style=3D"margin-left: 30.0px;"><strong>4.2 SQL Injection (SQLi)&nbsp;</s=
trong></p>
<p style=3D"margin-left: 30.0px;"><strong>Cause</strong>: An SQL injection =
occurs when input is submitted to a system and is interpreted as a SQLcomma=
nd. This happens when untrusted user input is concatenated into a SQL query=
 which is then executed against a database. If the user input is not saniti=
sed and the query is dynamically created with the unsanitised user input an=
d submitted to the database, malicious queries can be executed to read, mod=
ify, or delete information in the underlying database.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>
<p style=3D"margin-left: 30.0px;"><strong>Fix</strong>: The best way to avo=
id SQL injections is to create prepared statements for parameterized querie=
s where the prepared statements are stored in the program beforehand as a t=
emplate of sorts. Any untrusted input being used to form queries should als=
o be sanitised.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>
<p style=3D"margin-left: 30.0px;"><br></p>
<p style=3D"margin-left: 30.0px;"><strong>4.3 Reflected Cross Site Scriptin=
g (XSS)&nbsp;</strong></p>
<p style=3D"margin-left: 30.0px;"><strong>Cause</strong>: XSS allows an att=
acker to compromise the interactions that users have with a vulnerable appl=
ication. It is caused by data entering an application from an untrusted sou=
rce, typically from a request. When this malicious data is included in dyna=
mic content and is sent to a web browser without being validated for malici=
ous content XSS occurs. Reflected XSS occurs when the injected content is r=
eflected off the web server, such as in an error message, search result or =
any other response that includes some or all the input sent to the server a=
s part of the initial request.&nbsp;</p>
<p style=3D"margin-left: 30.0px;"><strong>Fix</strong>: Fixes are outlined =
in detail in the following URL: <a href=3D"https://confluence.srv.westpac.c=
om.au/display/SDEPKB/XSS+Prevention" rel=3D"nofollow">https://confluence.sr=
v.westpac.com.au/display/SDEPKB/XSS+Prevention</a>&nbsp;</p>
<ol>
<li>Never insert untrusted data except in allowed locations&nbsp;</li>
<li>HTML escape before inserting untrusted data into HTML Element content&n=
bsp;</li>
<li>Attribute escape before inserting untrusted data into HTML common attri=
butes&nbsp;</li>
<li>JavaScript escape before inserting untrusted data into JavaScript data =
values&nbsp;</li>
<li>CSS escape and strictly validate before inserting untrusted data into H=
TML style property values&nbsp;</li>
<li>URL escape before inserting untrusted data into HTML URL parameter valu=
es&nbsp;</li>
<li>Sanitize HTML markup with a library designed for the Job&nbsp;</li>
<li>Avoid JavaScript URL's&nbsp;</li>
<li>Use HTTPOnly cookie flag&nbsp;</li>
<li>Implement Content Security Policy&nbsp;</li>
<li>Use an Auto-Escaping template system&nbsp;</li>
<li>Properly use modern JS frameworks&nbsp;</li>
</ol>
<p><br></p>
<p style=3D"margin-left: 30.0px;"><strong>4.4 XML External Entity (XXE) Vul=
nerabilities&nbsp;</strong>&nbsp;</p>
<p style=3D"margin-left: 30.0px;"><strong>Cause:</strong> XXE is a vulnerab=
ility which allows an attacker to interfere with the way in which an applic=
ation processes XML data. An attacker may be able to view files on the appl=
ication server file system or interact with back-end or external systems th=
at the application itself can access. This happens in applications where XM=
L format is used to transmit data between the browser and the server, typic=
ally using a standard library or platform API to process the data on the se=
rver. The vulnerability arises when the XML specification has potentially d=
angerous features which are supported by standard parsers even if they are =
not normally used by the application. XXE can be used to execute several at=
tacks including retrieving files and performing Server-Side Request Forgery=
 (SSRF).&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>
<p style=3D"margin-left: 30.0px;"><strong>Fix</strong>: Most XXE vulnerabil=
ities arise because the application=E2=80=99s XML parsing library supports =
potentially dangerous XML features which the application often does not nee=
d or intend to use. The easiest and most effective way to prevent XXE is to=
 disable those features.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>
<p style=3D"margin-left: 30.0px;">It is typically sufficient to disable res=
olution of external entities and disable support for XInclude. This can usu=
ally be done via configuration or overriding default behaviour.&nbsp;&nbsp;=
</p>
<p style=3D"margin-left: 30.0px;"><br></p>
<p style=3D"margin-left: 30.0px;"><strong>4.5 Server-Side Request Forgery (=
SSRF)&nbsp;</strong></p>
<p style=3D"margin-left: 30.0px;"><strong>Cause</strong>:&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>
<p style=3D"margin-left: 30.0px;">SSRF is an attack vector that abuses an a=
pplication to interact with the internal/external network or the machine it=
self. One of the enablers for this vector is the mishandling of URLs, . SSR=
F is not limited to the HTTP protocol, even though in general the first req=
uest leverages it, yet the second request is performed by the application i=
tself, and thus it could be using different protocols (<em>e.g.,</em> FTP, =
SMB, SMTP, etc.) and schemes (<em>e</em>.g. file://, phar://, gopher://, da=
ta://, dict://, etc.). The protocol/scheme usage is highly dependent on the=
 application's requirements. If the application is vulnerable to <a href=3D=
"https://confluence.srv.westpac.com.au/display/SDEPKB/XXE+XML+External+Enti=
ty+Injection" rel=3D"nofollow">XML eXternal Entity (XXE)</a> then it can by=
 exploited to perform an SSRF attack.&nbsp;</p>
<p style=3D"margin-left: 30.0px;"><strong>Fix</strong>:&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>
<p style=3D"margin-left: 30.0px;">Sanitise and validate all client-supplied=
 input data. Enforce the URL schema, port, and destination with a positive =
allow list. Do not send raw responses to clients. Disable HTTP redirections=
. Be aware of the URL consistency to avoid attacks such as DNS rebinding an=
d =E2=80=9Ctime of check, time of use=E2=80=9D (TOCTOU) race conditions.&nb=
sp;&nbsp;</p>
<p style=3D"margin-left: 30.0px;">Do not mitigate SSRF via the use of a den=
y list or regular expression. Attackers have payload lists, tools, and skil=
ls to bypass deny lists.&nbsp;</p>
<p><em>For more details:</em>&nbsp;</p>
<p><a href=3D"https://confluence.srv.westpac.com.au/display/SDEPKB/Applicat=
ion+Security+Knowledge+Base" rel=3D"nofollow">Application Security Knowledg=
e Base - Engineering Knowledge Base - Westpac Enterprise Confluence</a>&nbs=
p;</p>
<p><br></p>
<h1 id=3D"Section2:CommonsecurityissuesfoundinAPIs&amp;recommendations-5Swa=
ggerHardening">5 Swagger Hardening&nbsp;</h1>
<p><strong>Cause</strong>:&nbsp; &nbsp;<br>
 All variables in the Swagger specification must be validated using a regex=
 or an enum or similar validation related to the data type, which restricts=
 the input values accepted by the API. When the appropriate operational ste=
ps noted by WDP are followed (see <a href=3D"https://confluence.srv.westpac=
.com.au/display/WDPIPAAS/Westpac+Digital+Platform+Home" rel=3D"nofollow">ht=
tps://confluence.srv.westpac.com.au/display/WDPIPAAS/Westpac+Digital+Platfo=
rm+Home</a>), these validations will flow into the associated code. To opt =
out of this validation mechanism imposes a risk to Westpac as it assumes th=
at no input is ever malicious, and we know for a fact that financial instit=
utions like us are constantly targeted by malicious actors. Your choice to =
enable this input validation makes a big difference!&nbsp;</p>
<p><strong>Fix</strong>:&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>
<p>As per security best practices, developers should know acceptable input =
format, data type and length, so that it can be validated. The argument tha=
t one cannot validate an input because you do not know if it will break som=
ething, or that you are not sure of the characters that may be present in t=
he input, is by itself a red flag. If this is the case, you need to clarify=
 the requirements and write tests, not skip input validation. Moreover, ple=
ase do not rely on the validation some other layer of API does. As per the =
defense in depth principle, each API is expected to do its due diligence by=
 knowing and validating ALL inputs that it handles.&nbsp;</p>
<p><br></p>
<p><strong><br></strong>&nbsp;</p>
<p><em>Additional details</em></p>
<p>More info can be found from the below links:&nbsp;<br><a href=3D"https:/=
/swagger.io/docs/specification/data-models/data-types/" class=3D"external-l=
ink" rel=3D"nofollow">https://swagger.io/docs/specification/data-models/dat=
a-types/</a>&nbsp;<br><a href=3D"https://swagger.io/docs/specification/data=
-models/enums/" class=3D"external-link" rel=3D"nofollow">https://swagger.io=
/docs/specification/data-models/enums/</a>&nbsp;</p>
<p><br></p>
<p>Alternatively, please consult WDP/ISG where necessary.&nbsp;</p>
</div><strong style=3D"text-decoration: underline" class=3D"pageTitle" data=
-content-id=3D"1173255035">Section 3: FAQs&nbsp;</strong>
<div class=3D"tabs-pane active-pane" id=3D"b7a649a3-9c35-4976-bc9c-1e6593b1=
ec19-1173255035">
<div class=3D"table-wrap">
<table class=3D"wrapped relative-table confluenceTable" style=3D"width: 100=
.0%;">
<colgroup>
<col style=3D"width: 24.825%;">
<col style=3D"width: 75.175%;">
</colgroup>
<tbody>
<tr>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">Question</th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">Answer</th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd"><strong>What do I do if I have a new WDP compone=
nt which requires scanning?&nbsp;</strong></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<div class=3D"content-wrapper">
<p>You must reach out to the AppSec team to create a new component in forti=
fy for the new WDP component. You will be provided with a SCAAS token (PJVE=
RID).<br>
 For more details on how WDP components are configured to be scanned, visit=
 this WDP space <em><u><strong>here</strong></u></em>. <a class=3D"confluen=
ce-userlink user-mention" data-username=3D"M042904" href=3D"/display/~M0429=
04" data-linked-resource-id=3D"7251998" data-linked-resource-version=3D"2" =
data-linked-resource-type=3D"userinfo" data-base-url=3D"https://confluence.=
srv.westpac.com.au">Anirban Basu</a> to provide link.</p>
</div></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd"><strong>Why has the digital signature not been p=
rovided in SIT?&nbsp;</strong></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd"><p>The only reason a digital signature would not=
 have be provided in SIT, is if there are new <strong>Medium</strong> and <=
strong>High </strong>rated issues found in the build. Check the automated r=
esults and fix the findings before redeploying to SIT. <span>&nbsp;</span><=
/p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd"><strong>What if I am facing an NPM audit issue w=
hich has a transitive dependency?&nbsp;</strong></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">If this is the case, please reach out to your Ap=
pSec consultant or send an email to&nbsp;<span>securecodereviewmailbox.</sp=
an></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd"><p><strong>What if I am not receiving an email w=
ith the automated results when I deploy to SIT?&nbsp;</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd"><p><span>Another developer may have deployed the=
 build to SIT.&nbsp;</span><span>Please check with the developer who has co=
mmitted&nbsp;the code previously as they would have received automated emai=
l with the code scan results from the securecodereviewmailbox.</span><span>=
&nbsp;</span></p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd"><p><strong>Why is my deployment failing in SVP/P=
ROD?&nbsp;</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd"><p><span>If a digital signature was not provided=
 for a specific build in SIT, that build will also fail in SVP and PROD. Ch=
eck that the digital signature was provided in SIT for that specific build.=
</span><span>&nbsp;</span></p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd"><p><strong>How can I get access to Fortify?&nbsp=
;</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd"><p><span>Please raise a Fortify request here in =
Tech Service Portal here&nbsp;</span><a href=3D"https://snprodwestpac.servi=
ce-now.com/wbgtechserviceportal?id=3Dwp_home" class=3D"external-link" rel=
=3D"nofollow"><span>https://snprodwestpac.service-now.com/wbgtechservicepor=
tal?id=3Dwp_home</span></a><span style=3D"color: rgb(23,43,77);">&nbsp;and =
enter "</span><span style=3D"color: rgb(23,43,77);">Fortify</span><span sty=
le=3D"color: rgb(23,43,77);">" into the query field.</span></p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd"><strong>I have deployed in SIT, what are my next=
 steps?&nbsp;</strong></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd"><span>Please visit our FAQ page to review next s=
teps <a href=3D"https://confluence.srv.westpac.com.au/display/ASICS/DIY%3A+=
Application+Security+help+guide" rel=3D"nofollow">DIY: Application Security=
 help guide - Application Security - Westpac Enterprise Confluence</a></spa=
n><span>.</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd"><p><strong>How do I re-scan a component after fi=
xing a medium or high rated vulnerability?&nbsp;</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd"><p><span>Once you have fixed medium or high rate=
d issues, you will need to redeploy to SIT environment for a scan. If all i=
ssues are fixed, you will then receive a digital signature and you will be =
able to deploy to higher environments. </span><span>&nbsp;</span></p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd"><strong>What is not in scope for AppSec Code Rev=
iew?&nbsp;</strong></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<ul>
<li><span>Proxy APIs -&nbsp;Proxy APIs are not in scope for scanning as the=
y don't contain any source code to scan</span></li>
<li><span>Non-production source code (I.e., test files)</span><span>&nbsp;<=
/span></li>
<li><span>Kafka Topics</span></li>
</ul></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd"><strong>What if there is no fix for a NPM Audit =
issues in my component?&nbsp;</strong></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd"><p><span>If your NPM audit issue do not have a p=
atch, comment the same in Fortify and let your AppSec consultant know so th=
ey can help you with next steps.</span></p><p><span>If a library does not h=
ave a patch for an extended period (More than 6-12 months), it would not be=
 best practice to continue using it.&nbsp;</span><span>&nbsp;</span></p></t=
d>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd"><strong>What if there is a fix for a NPM Audit i=
ssues in mu component but its breaking the build?&nbsp;</strong></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd"><span>If your NPM audit issue has a patch, but i=
s breaking the build, comment the same in Fortify and let your AppSec consu=
ltant know so they can help you with next steps.</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd"><strong>What are AppSec standard business hours?=
&nbsp;</strong></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd"><p><span>Please refer to </span><a href=3D"https=
://confluence.srv.westpac.com.au/display/ASICS/AppSec+Out-Of-Office+busines=
s+hours+support" rel=3D"nofollow"><span>AppSec Out-Of-Office business hours=
 support</span><span>&nbsp;</span></a>.</p></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<p></p>
    </div>
</body>
</html>
